                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\n\n--- Comment #10 from Elin Waring ("
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "link",
                                "url": "mailto:elin.waring@gmail.com",
                                "text": "elin.waring@gmail.com"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": ") ---\nYes I agree about the likely history.  And specifically in the case of your\noriginal example this is relevant.\n\n"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_preformatted",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "> factor(c(1.5, 1.0))\n[1] 1.5 1  \nLevels: 1 1.5\n> factor(c(\"1.5\", \"1.0\"))\n[1] 1.5 1.0\nLevels: 1.0 1.5\n\n\n"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\n\nSo the casting to factor that happens in the interaction functions results in\nthe loss of the \".0\" which then impacts the creation of the interaction terms\nin what I would say is an unplanned way.   And that explains my original\nobservation.  And my original thought of casting to character has the same\nissue. \n\nI do think that it was probably that people focused on dealing with the created\nduplicates rather than on why the duplicates where created."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
